text: I am going to see "The Founder" today. Obviously, I haven't seen the movie yet and have no opinion on it. However, I've been reading reviews of the film and some critics stand out because they clearly disliked the movie simply because it's about a thoroughlyÂ unlikable bastard who succeeded. Apparently, for those critics, screen biographies should all beÂ inspiring andÂ uplifting stories, unmitigated hagiographies like Spielberg's "Lincoln," or going a bit further back, "Gandhi." Well, maybe those critics can assuage their disappointment by watching "42" again, a veritable treasure trove of biopic clichÃ©s. Or, if they want to see the sort of fiction Hollywood USED to be capable of when making a movie about an absolute stinker, they could drown their sorrow in the sugary goodness of "Yankee Doodle Dandy." Or, if they lack a gag threshold, they should find a copy of the WORST biopic ever, "The Babe Ruth Story," starring William Bendix. You know, the Babe didn't actually die of cancer, it was shame afterÂ experiencing the blubbery bathos of that movie.

He didn't fully look over my application before offering me the job. Anyway, we had to learn about Ray Kroc and his persistence. I learned quite a bit at that job.
